<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The long, dark, looped arm of the distiphallus is an unmistakable characteristic of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Frick" authorityYear="1954" class="Insecta" family="Gelsemiaceae" genus="Phytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phytomyza persicae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persicae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Phytomyza persicae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and should be examined to confidently differentiate it from similar species such as the 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Aquifoliaceae" genus="Ilex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ilex" order="Aquifoliales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ilex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
leaf miners, which are nearly identical externally. In Europe, the very similar P. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">heringiana</emphasis>
Hendel occurs on apple (
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="Malus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Malus domestica" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="domestica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Malus domestica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Papp, L" journalOrPublisher="Pars Ltd, Hungary. Nagykovacsi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B190" refString="Papp, L, Cerny, M, 2020. Agromyzidae (Diptera) of Hungary (Vol. 4). Phytomyzinae III. Pars Ltd, Hungary. Nagykovacsi" title="Agromyzidae (Diptera) of Hungary (Vol. 4). Phytomyzinae III." year="2020">
Papp and 
